/p>\n<p>But if you have some IRC log/quote file that captures this fine moment or know of a mailing list discussion where this happened, can you please pass along?</p>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Interprete/~4/6YMGldGdQgg\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" />" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Interprete/~3/6YMGldGdQgg/" (19073 23962) old 35 nil nil ((title nil "Biella Coleman: Dear Lazy Web: RTFM-in-Action") (guid nil "http://gabriellacoleman.org/blog/?p=1717") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Interprete/~3/6YMGldGdQgg/") (description nil "  <p>So I am currently working on a section of my book that examines the duality/tension between sharing and self-reliance among hackers. I have some great examples from IRC of sharing but none of RTFMing, which indeed, is more rare. Do you have in your quote file some funny example of RTFM (or a kindred ‘eff you’) or know of a mailing list discussion where this happened? I would love to include in the book.</p>\n<p>Here is a bit more concrete example of my claims:</p>\n<blockquote><p>\nOn the one hand, hackers speak of the importance of learning from others and construe knowledge production as a collective enterprise—this rhetoric is often matched in practice by truly generous and copious acts of constant sharing. In any given minute of the day, I can head over to one of the developers IRC channels and there will be some developers asking a question, getting an answer, and giving thanks. On the other hand, hackers at times express an extreme commitment to individual self-reliance, which can be at times displayed in a quite abrasive and elitist tone. Hacker discourse creates fine discriminations among the projects of individual programmers and valorizes independent control over technical environments and production</p></blockquote>\n<p>I have some great examples of sharing-in-action on IRC. I also have a great analytical discussion of RTFM among DD’s but what I don’t have is an RTFM in action.</p>\n<p>I can 1) spend